<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from NAPO</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from NAPO</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:80%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:80%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:14pt; line-height:80%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:14pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Napo, the trade union and professional association for probation and family court staff</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Under the umbrella term of “Transforming Rehabilitation”, the government is planning a major reorganisation of the Probation Service in England and Wales.  Their case is that the Offender Management Act of 2007 allows the Secretary of State to deliver probation services directly himself or by entering into a contract with another party.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The reorganisation will see all 35 probation trusts dissolved in a few months</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> time and replaced with a National Probation Service (NPS) and 21 Community Rehabilitation Companies (CRCs).  The CRCs will be subject to price competitive tendering and it is expected that the bidders will include companies such as Atos, Capita, G4S, Serco, A4E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Carillion</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Sodexo.  There will also be some mutual arrangements with financial backing by th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ese</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or other </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">private companies.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Offender Rehabilitation Bill, currently making its way through Parliament, will give the private providers the responsibilities of risk management, offender supervision and interventions for “low” and “medium” risk offenders.  High risk cases and victim work will remain in the public NPS.  Advice to the courts and Parole Board will also remain with the NPS.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Bill provides for mandatory 12 months supervision for those sentenced to less than a year in custody.  It also provides for a new community sentence, the “Rehabilitation Activity Requirement” in which the Court will only be advised of the number of days the activity will be held on rather than what that activity should consist of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as is currently the case.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The changes to be made under the Act and the Bill are inextricably linked.  It is proposed that the privatisation of up to 70% of the Probation Service will pay for the sup</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ervision of the under-12 months</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> custodial community.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Reorganisation under the Offender Management Act 2007</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Privatisation</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Probation Service has some current experience of privatisation.  Outsourced facilities management has resulted </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">private providers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">travelling the length and breadth of the country to carry out very small tasks resulting in delays and wasted time.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Serco currently manages the Community Payback scheme in London with a sub-contract to London Probation Trust.  All the local offices were closed and the work is run from a single call centre with a third less staff.  Our members have complained about offender projects being closed without warning, of a lack of robust evidence when cases come to court for enforcement action, a lack of proper health and safety, lack of safeguarding procedures for those aged under 18 and a lack of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proper</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> record keeping.  These concerns were the subject of a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">BBC “</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Newsnight</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> investigation and the Community Payback contract is now </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">subject of a Public Accounts Committee investigation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Electronic monitoring (EM) contracts have been held by Serco and G4S and both are currently being investigated for fraud.  A 2012 study by Policy Exchange “The Future of Corrections: Exploring the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Use of Electronic Monitoring” </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">found that the EM contract had failed to deliver any reduction in offending or value for money for the taxpayer.  They criticise centralised procurement and lengthy contracts for a lack of innovation resulting in unimaginative uses of tagging that do not meet the needs of sentencers, practitioners or the community.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">By comparison i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t currently costs £1.22 per day for EM in the United States and £13.14 in England &amp; Wales.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Policy Exchange report goes on to describe the problem of “gaming” i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n private contracts: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Over the last 13 years, the number of practices within the electronic monitoring providers have been exposed, typically by whistle-blowers or former employees.  The ability to game the system has in large part been aided by the extent to which electronic monitoring has been outsourced and the extremely limited visibility </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">practitioners and contract managers have of the live systems operated by suppliers.  One former field monitoring officer explained how “[control centre] staff on occasions would request that MM [alternative monitoring visits] were fabricated so as to avoid a financial penalty being accrued.”  Other examples of gaming include </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a strong incentive on the part of the service provider to boost revenue by carrying out as many install and de-installs as possible.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Taken together, the evidence from privatisation casts doubt on the claim that it can “deliver more for less”.  On the basis of the evidence so far, we would urge extreme caution in rolling out a model of outsourcing across the whole of England &amp; Wales.  We are not yet convinced that the Ministry of Justice (MoJ) has the capability or necessary experience to effectively oversee contracts.  In any event, we believe that commissioning should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">locally </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rather than centrally driven.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Napo proposes that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 42.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Existing outsourced contracts should be fully evaluated before the model is rolled out any further.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 42.5pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">privatization of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> offender management for low and medium risk offenders is a step into the unknown and must be piloted in a discrete area before any national roll out.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Fragmentation, Accountability and Public Safety</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Risk of harm is dynamic.  That is to say that the risk posed by offenders changes.  In around 25% of cases, risk assessment will change during the life of an order or licence.  The Transforming Rehabilitation (TR) model proposes that if the risk assessment of an offender changes from low/medium to high, the public NPS will assess the case and the management of the case can transferred from the CRC to the NPS.  In our professional experience, risk changes need to be acted upon immediately in order to protect the public.  If an offender needs to be recalled to prison in an emergency, the recall recommendatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n needs to be actioned within two </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hours.  This will be slowed down if the action is to be undertaken by different agencies using different IT systems and located in different places.  In other words, there is a risk an offender will fall between the cracks.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">“End to End Offender Management” is a concept arising from the Desistence research which found that a key element in reducing the risk of reoffending is the relationship between the practitioner and offender.  End to end proposes that there should be a single “offender manager” for an offender throughout the life of the order or licence.  This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> relationship</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risks being broken in the 25% of cases where risk changes.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At oral</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> hearings, the parole board relies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on evidence from probation practitioners who know the offender.  There will be difficulties in providing evidence if the person responsible for the recall is not the same person who has worked with the offender.  The preparation of risk management plans, provided by the NPS, on the basis of services provided wholly by the CRC risk being confused and incoherent.  It is not yet clear where the lines of accountability and professional oversight will be.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In their response to the TR Consultation (February 2013), the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Magistrates’ Association wrote: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“The Magistrates’ Association has concerns about exactly how the residual public sector probation service will assure itself about the risk management of up to 200,000 offenders  for whom it will have no responsibility and with whom it will have no supervisory contact.  Medium risk and even low risk offenders still have multiple complex needs including large numbers of domestic violence cases.  It will be disastrous for sentence confidence in the new arrangements if offenders being managed by private contractors appear in court and there appears to be any lack of communication, any lack of information on how risk was being managed or any mistrust between the private sector offender manager and the public sector official giving advice to the court.”</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:50%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Napo proposes that:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:50%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45.97pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Offender management should be retained in the public sector.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Payment by Results, “Gaming” and Conflict of Interest</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:50%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A new system of Payment by Results is to be introduced; possibly accounting for between 7-10% of the total value of the contract (the exact amount has not yet been made clear by the MoJ).  The “result” will be based on the ability of the provider to reduce re-offending but, again, there are concerns.  The Social Market Foundation found that the current proposals include a perverse incentive to allow offending to rise and the company could still make a profit.  The PbR system allows for a margin of 3% statistical insignificance either way.  In other words, the CRC could allow offending to rise by 3% and still get full payment under the 90-93% “fee for service”.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:50%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In his August 2013 report, the Director of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">SMF noted that: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“On these plans providers face incentives to cut frontline costs and allow reoffending rates to creep up.  If they are implemented the scheme will reward failure and penalise success. Doing so would be setting the scheme up to fail for victims, taxpayers and offenders.”  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Ministry of Justice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> itself</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has noted a potential for gaming within a profit making justice sector.  There are concerns that offenders will either be seen as cheap or expensive in terms of their ability to make a profit.  In other words, offenders who have a profile of low recidivism could be cherry picked and those with a higher</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> risk of recidivism may not be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> seen as worth investing in because they are less likely to end in a result.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:50%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Napo’s view is that reducing re-offending is a vital part of probation work but it does not recognise the complexity of offender services.  Reducing the risk of harm is also vital (even if non-harmful offending still occurs) but this is given no value under the PbR financial model.  One of our concern</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is that complex offenders might be more at risk of recall- in order to move the financial risk back to prison.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The MoJ has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> recognised a potential financial disincentive for the CRC to transfer the case to the NPS where there is escalating risk.  For that reason, the potential for a PbR payment will remain with the CRC regardless of who manages the case.  Notwithstanding our concerns about the principle here, the provision of anti-gaming measures highlights the risks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">inherent</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the TR proposals.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Offender Management Act 2007 created 35 Probation Trusts with the ability to commission services locally.  The TR proposals abolish these commissioning bodies and replace them with 21 CRCs and seven regional NPS divisions.  They are not coterminous with the Police and Crime Commissioners or police forces or local authorities.  Several different CRCs will be aligned to the NPS divisions which risks the NPS side of offender management being spread very thin.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In Napo’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> view, this potentially increases the delay in being able to respond to changing levels of risk.  Not least because of the great geographical a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eas to be covered.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The TR proposals create the possibility for conflicts of interest.  The introduction of profit into offender services could create </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> potential for a private company </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to profit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">a combination of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">imprisonment, electronic monitoring and offender management.  We are concerned about what appears to be a lack of transparency and scrutiny of the potential risks here.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In February 2013, London Councils (representing the boroughs and the City) responded to the TR consultat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ion with the following concerns: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“We are concerned that the model of national commissioning with large contract package areas may have the opposite effect with a narrowing of the market of providers, with only large providers being able to compete for contracts. Our concern is the capacity that the small providers realistically have to come together in consortia to deliver within the proposed new system. We are also concerned that the payment by results model may squeeze out small providers of often niche support, thereby losing often excellent services from the market of providers.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Napo proposes that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.07pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Any PbR model should be properly piloted as it applies to offender management with a control group.  The pilot should be properly evaluated before any national roll out.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.07pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Proper localism relies on smaller commissioning bodies.  The Trust model for Probation can be used to greater effect to meet the government’s aims of increasing diversity of provision and supervision of the under-12months’ custodial community.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 53.07pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The government should publish any information about the potential conflict of interest issues and for these risks to be scrutinised by Parliament.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Partnership Work</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Partnership work is vital in probation and there are vast numbers of examples of where this has worked well.  Relationships between probation, police, local authorities, children’s services, the NHS and the third sector have been built up over many years with service level agreements and information sharing protocols.  These arrangements take time to evolve and the current plans pose a risk which need</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> safeguarding against.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">London Councils made the following point in their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">response to the TR consultation: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“Introducing new providers into offender management has the potential to affect these existing local partnerships, where local probation trusts currently play a key role. These are often partnerships that have taken years to build. In order for these local partnerships to be maintained, new providers will need to be able to integrate with existing partnership arrangements. For example, effective data sharing protocols with new lead providers will be vital to ensure offender management data is shared in a timely manner with the local partners.”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Integrated Offender Management Model (IOM) is a collaborative model led by the police and probation with input from other agencies and the third sector.  The IOM scheme works intensively with o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ffenders with a high risk of re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">offending.  This includes, on a non-statutory basis, those sentenced to unde</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r-12 months custody.  It involve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s intensive supervision, bespoke interventions and close joint work between agencies.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In September 2013, Sheffield Hallam University published a cost/benefit analysis into the IOM project in Surry &amp; Sussex Probation Trust.  It found that reoffending had reduced among the IOM cohort by 52.3%.  They found that for ever</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">y £1 spent on IOM, over five</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> years the taxpayer would save £1.59.  London Councils found that IOM in the London Borough of Islington cut the cost of crime from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£523,264 to £295,108 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mainly by reducing domestic burglary.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Napo proposes that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45.97pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The government publishes any potential risks to partnership work and failures to service delivery as part of Transforming Rehabilitation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45.97pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That new proposals for partnership working are piloted before a national roll out.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45.97pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That any organisation bidding for probation work must demonstrate how partnership working will exist under the new arrangements.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45.97pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That the government must open up to public scrutiny the provisions for information sharing and data protection with new providers of offender management.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Changes proposed in the Offender Rehabilitation Bill</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Offender Rehabilitation Bill seeks to deal with the high rates of reoffending among those offenders who are sentenced to less than 12 months custody but have no statutory supervision on release.  That is a laudable aim and one broadly supported by Napo.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The government has quoted a voluntary pilot project at HMP Peterborough for those offenders which is run jointly between Serco and the St Giles Trust.  The MoJ figures quote a 12% reduction in re-offending although they have noted that this pilot will not be completed until 2014, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">that there is no control group and that the figures do not include cautions.  For that reason, we would urge restraint in projecting these figures onto a mandatory nation-wide model.  In any event, our view is the success of this pilot i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s dwarfed by the success of IOM across England and Wales.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Mandatory Supervision for the under-12 months’ Custodial Community</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The government’s proposals mean that any offender sentenced to less than 12 months will be supervised in the community until the end of a 12 month period.  The aim of the new licence period is stated as rehabilitation but it should be noted that there are penalties for non-compliance including electronic monitoring, unpaid work and up to 14 days additional imprisonment.  So it would be right to say that there is a punitive element to the supervision.  It is also right to say that there would be some instances in which an offender sentenced to less than 12 months would be subject to more statutory supervision than an offender sentenced to more than 12 months under the existing rules.  This creates an anomaly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and it is vital that this should </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">be examined further.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Napo’s view is that there should be greater flexibility in this new licence provision.  Currently, sentencing is based on the sentencing guidelines and based on proportionality to the offence committed and the particular circumstances of the offender.  The new proposals somewhat undermine that.  While some offenders may require greater resources, this will not apply across the board and we would not advocate an indiscriminate use of state resources.  Additionally, we are concerned that the Bill provides for CRC staff to impose additional licence conditions which the provider may ultimately profit from. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The sanctions applied in the new licence may be disproportionate to those offenders who struggle to comply.  Where a short term prison sentence has been imposed to deal with a breach of community supervision, it may be counter-productive for that sentence to include a new mandatory period of supervision.  Women offenders, those with mental health problems, homeless offenders, offenders with learning difficulties and others with complex needs may be more at risk of sanctions.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">On 12 November 2013, the Joint Committee on Human Rights noted concerns that there should be judicial discretion on whether or not licence supervision is needed and for how long rather than a mandatory 12 month period.  The Committee also noted concerns about the impact of the new licence on women offenders, young offenders and those in the black and minority ethnic communities.  They also noted the government’s projections that the new licence will increase, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not reduce, the number of short-term</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> prison sentences.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Napo proposes that:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45.97pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Each short term prisoner should be assessed by a public sector officer to determine licence conditions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45.97pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There should be a provision for the licence to be revoked on the grounds of good progress.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45.97pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That the new licences should be piloted on a voluntary basis to test results (we are not convinced that mandatory supervision is required).</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45.97pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sanctions must only be applied on the basis of public sector advice to the Court.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45.97pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That the new proposals are fully evaluated in terms of equality and human rights.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Rehabilitation Activity Requirement</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Offender Rehabilitation Bill provides for a new type of community sentence.  This proposal at pre-sentence will state the total number of days the intervention should take place on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> but the exact nature of the activity will be specified post-sentence.  The government’s aim here is to increase flexibility to attend to “what works”.  This style of proposal has been piloted in the West Yorkshire Probation Trust and we would advise that the evidence from this model is evaluated for effectiveness.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, our case would be that flexibility for practitioners has been increased already with the New Practice Framework which took away the previous rigid and target-based style of offender management.  We would echo the sentiments </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the Magistrates’ Association: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">“The Probation Service relaxed its National Standards in 2011 to allow practitioners to concentrate on ‘what works’ rather than on following procedures.  We have not allowed enough time to see </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the results of this.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">While </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Napo advocates a greater degree of flexibility in terms of our work with offenders, safeguards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">need to be in place </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">take account of the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> great disparity between providers.  We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are also </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">concerned that the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> proposed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> relationship between the courts and the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">private </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sector </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">allow this flexibility to take </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">place. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> In any case t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hat relationship will take time to form and we think it should be established before the new regime is in place.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Napo </span><a name="_GoBack"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">proposes</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 45.97pt; padding-left:3.68pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The new sentence should be delayed until the proposed CRCs have been in place for 2 years and then on a pilot basis. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Appendix 1</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">SUMMARY OF PROPOSALS</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Napo would ask the Justice Select Committee to consider the following</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Existing outsourced contracts should be fully evaluated before the model is rolled out any further.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">privatization of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> offender management for low and medium risk offenders is a step into the unknown and must be piloted in a discrete area before any national roll out.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Offender management should be retained in the public sector.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Any PbR model should be properly piloted as it applies to offender management with a control group.  The pilot should be properly evaluated before any national roll out.   </span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Proper localism relies on smaller commissioning bodies.  The Trust model for Probation can be used to greater effect to meet the government’s aims of increasing diversity of provision and supervision of the under-12months’ custodial community.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 29.67pt; padding-left:6.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The government should publish any information about the potential conflict of interest issues and for these risks </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to be scrutinised by Parliament.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The government publishes any potential risks to partnership work and failures to service delivery as part of Transforming Rehabilitation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That new proposals for partnership working are piloted before a national roll out.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 29pt; padding-left:7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That any organisation bidding for probation work must demonstrate how partnership working will exist under the new arrangements.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 29pt; padding-left:7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That the government must open up to public scrutiny the provisions for information sharing and data protection with new providers of offender management.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 32.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Each short term prisoner should be assessed by a public sector officer to determine licence conditions.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 29pt; padding-left:7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There should be a provision for the licence to be revoked on the grounds of good progress.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That the new licences should be piloted on a voluntary basis to test results (we are not convinced that mandatory supervision is required).</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sanctions must only be applied on the basis of public sector advice to the Court.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That the new proposals are fully evaluated in terms of equality and human rights.</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The new sentence should be delayed until the proposed CRCs have been in place for 2 years and then on a pilot basis. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">8</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>